; &gt; &gt; path. The problem is not with siddhis per se, it is with misusing \n&gt; them\n&gt; &gt; &gt; or commercializing them or hanging on to them. Any sadhaka who can\n&gt; &gt; &gt; gain a siddhi, can also let go of that siddhi whenever he/she wants.\n&gt; &gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt; Speaking of Karma, everything has a karma of it&#39;s own. Tantra, as it\n&gt; &gt; &gt; stands today, is roughly divided into two major geographic and\n&gt; &gt; &gt; philosophical demarcations. The style practiced in South India -\n&gt; &gt; &gt; mostly Dakshina Margi - and that practiced in Bengal and adjacent\n&gt; &gt; &gt; areas - mostly Vama Margi. In my personal opinion, the adherents of\n&gt; &gt; &gt; the path in both cases, generally speaking, have been trapped in two\n&gt; &gt; &gt; delusions born out of collateral byproducts of their respective \n&gt; paths.\n&gt; &gt; &gt; The first step of Shakti sadhana is generating shakti. Second step is\n&gt; &gt; &gt; holding the shakti. Third step is channeling the shakti. In view of\n&gt; &gt; &gt; this, one school of Tantra that is prevalent today has tied itself up\n&gt; &gt; &gt; in too much of technicalities, such that on an average they forget to\n&gt; &gt; &gt; capture shakti (here shakti means energy, not Shakti the supreme\n&gt; &gt; &gt; Goddess). WHile the other school is able to generate and hold shakti\n&gt; &gt; &gt; much better, only to commercialize the same and/or misuse it\n&gt; &gt; &gt; (generally speaking, expcetions are there too). End result, both\n&gt; &gt; &gt; eventually do not end up producing enough genuine Tantrik saints.\n&gt; &gt; &gt; &lt;&lt; i am wondering &quot;if at all&quot; and &quot;what kind&quot; of karmic liabilities\n&gt; &gt; &gt; one might be getting into ?&gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt; A fair exchange is never a robbery, as Vimalananda says.\n&gt; &gt; &gt; Theoretically, when the *right person* performs many of the things\n&gt; &gt; &gt; mentioned in that blog, (and some of the stuff the