nging on to them.\n              Any sadhaka who can &lt;br&gt;\n              &gt; &gt; gain a siddhi, can also let go of that siddhi\n              whenever he/she wants.&lt;br&gt;\n              &gt; &gt;&lt;br&gt;\n              &gt; &gt; Speaking of Karma, everything has a karma of\n              it&#39;s own. Tantra, as it &lt;br&gt;\n              &gt; &gt; stands today, is roughly divided into two major\n              geographic and &lt;br&gt;\n              &gt; &gt; philosophical demarcations. The style practiced\n              in South India - &lt;br&gt;\n              &gt; &gt; mostly Dakshina Margi - and that practiced in\n              Bengal and adjacent &lt;br&gt;\n              &gt; &gt; areas - mostly Vama Margi. In my personal\n              opinion, the adherents of &lt;br&gt;\n              &gt; &gt; the path in both cases, generally speaking, have\n              been trapped in two &lt;br&gt;\n              &gt; &gt; delusions born out of collateral byproducts of\n              their respective paths. &lt;br&gt;\n              &gt; &gt; The first step of Shakti sadhana is generating\n              shakti. Second step is &lt;br&gt;\n              &gt; &gt; holding the shakti. Third step is channeling the\n              shakti. In view of &lt;br&gt;\n              &gt; &gt; this, one school of Tantra that is prevalent\n              today has tied itself up &lt;br&gt;\n              &gt; &gt; in too much of technicalities, such that on an\n              average they forget to &lt;br&gt;\n              &gt; &gt; capture shakti (here shakti means energy, not\n              Shakti the supreme &lt;br&gt;\n              &gt; &gt; Goddess). WHile the other school is able to\n              generate and hold shakti &lt;br&gt;\n              &gt; &gt; much better, only to commercialize the same\n              and/or misuse it &lt;br&gt;\n              &gt; &gt; (generally speaking, expcetions are there too).\n              End result, both &lt;br&gt;\n   